7366839152286928171.voice_to_text: A major new poll released by Axio shows that college students don't really care about the protests that are ongoing on campuses. A survey over 12 college students show that the conflict in the Middle East was only cared about by 13% of those survey. These numbers aren't really surprising at all. This movement is a mess. Part of what is causing the problem is this movement is surprisingly ineffective at using social media. Instead of using it to raise sympathy for their cause, it's mainly being used to give the movement itself a false impression of how popular this movement is, and then to bully people who question the movement itself. This kind of echo chamber. You can maintain the belief that it's everyone else that's failing, when really it's the movement itself that's failing on every level. But rather than dwell on the failures, let's talk about solutions. The goal of any movement like this is to raise awareness and sympathy for your cause and to turn that sympathy into action. Problem with taking direct actions like encampments, destroying property, disrupting civic life, and then making hostage like demands to get you to stop, is you push more people away than you pull in. Actions themselves create fear and anger, which are both antithetical to sympathy and can inadvertently create sympathy for the opposing cause. There's another approach called a dilemma action, which is an indirect, non aggressive form of protest where the goal is to provoke a dilemma. For the opposition, where they look absurd no matter how they respond. For example, in 1982, in response to Soviet propaganda, Polish citizens started taking their televisions for walks, and wheelbarrows and strollers during the Soviet news hours. This created a situation where the government would have to arrest people for walking their television, which would then be covered in the news itself, creating the dilemma. Not only would it look absurd, but they'd have to explain why people were walking their televisions, exposing their own propaganda and spreading the message of the protesters. For them, cause of that dilemma, the government didn't do anything, which conceded ground to the Polish resistance movement, enabling them to broaden support for resisting the Soviet system. George Washington University recently used this technique against the protesters, when they hung a huge American flag in the backdrop of the protests. And the contrast put the protesters in a really negative way, while maintaining the integrity of the university. As standing up for the rights of all. Which increase their support to resist the protesters. The reason this work is because of your movement is only focus on what you're going to do and how you can express your English to your audience. It becomes self absorbed. I think we're seeing a lot of that, which is why they become blind. How antisocial this movement has become. But if you're thinking in terms of a dilemma action, you're thinking of your social movement as a Social interaction between you, your opposition, and most importantly, the rest of society. Society is the audience. They are the people you're trying to convince. They are the ones holding the sympathy that you need. But here's the question. How do you do that? What does a dilemma action look like for this movement? Let's hear some suggestions in the comments.

7374746572590042400.voice_to_text: Ah, it's a beautiful day in the apartheid where women are able to wear whatever they want. Videos like this will always annoy me because they fundamentally misunderstand what apartheid actually is. Because apartheid is not simply like in South Africa, people being banished to the Bantu stands. Although Israel does do this in the West Bank, keeping Palestinians hemmed within small spaces and not allowing them to move freely, the fact is, is that apartheid is best explained as a different system of legal rule for the national majority and the national minority. And even in this space, TEL Aviv, where this woman is able to find women wearing hijabs, the thing is, is that in the late 1980s, a TEL Aviv judge sentenced an Israeli boy who would kill the Palestinian boy six months of community service. And Israel has more and more been trying to further this legal discrimination. For example, last year, Israeli politicians like Itamar Bengavir attempted to get a law passed where Palestinians who committed sexual assault with nationalistic motivations would get double the sentences of Jewish people. And take Israel's 2,018 nation state law, which has been described as distinctly apartheid esque because it made it so that only Jewish people were allowed to exercise self determination, which doesn't make sense when there are 2 million Palestinians living within the land. It also degraded Arabic from an official language of the state to one of special significance when Hebrew has only been spoken in Palestine since The 1920s, really. And even then it had to be Learned by the Israeli settlers, because not even the Jewish people who had lived in Palestine for generations actually spoke Hebrew. And it also made settlement of Palestinian land and national value. So how could it possibly be that Palestinians are treated equally within Israeli society? And although Israelis like to act as if the West Bank is some different place to TEL Aviv, the fact is, is that Hebron is only an hour and a half away from TEL Aviv, and in her bronze, there are literally roads which only Jewish people are allowed to walk on. And also in the early 20, Israel literally trialed segregated buses for Palestinians and Jewish people. So this idea that just because you can find someone wearing a hijab in TEL Aviv is like me going to London, filming random black people who are clearly rich, and then stating that there is no racial inequality in the UK. However, if I was to scratch just below the surface, I would find that black and minority ethnicity groups are twice as likely to be living in poverty than white people. There are so many different facets which make Israel an apartheid state. There's articles talking about how there's even medical apartheid, because Palestinians from the Gaza Strip with terminal illnesses or serious illnesses that cannot be treated with Gaza's rather poor health care service because of years of Israeli degradation of it, are just Simply not allowed to leave. So as the saying goes, looks can be deceiving. And just because you can find someone who looks different to you within a society does not mean that there is a quality or that Israel is not an apartheid state.

7367798553760042283.video_description: A group of students stood up and walked out of VCU’s graduation ceremony on Saturday morning in Richmond as Governor Glenn Youngkin (R - Virginia) delivered his commencement address. Prior to the event, multiple groups, including the school’s NAACP chapter and a group called ‘Not Welcome at VCU’ said graduates were willing to walk out of the ceremony when Youngkin spoke.  VCU students who spoke at a recent Board of Visitors meeting said they were upset with Youngkin’s perceived interference with VCU’s now rejected racial literacy requirement.  They also expressed objections to Youngkin’s views on LGBTQ+ rights, healthcare, and his response to police breaking up a pro-Palestine protest.  “Yes, VCU has a bipartisan tradition of inviting gubernatorial speakers to commencement,” explained one student in the meeting. “But progress has never been made without challenging tradition. And our students and faculty cannot truly be Rams. If we were not headstrong, and we’d not headbutt that which we do not like.” Earlier this week, Governor Youngkin responded to students saying they would protest the commencement saying, “I firmly believe it can be a great day of celebration. I think that anyone who thinks they’re going to disrupt this for their own personal goals, I think is misguided.”

7366227427053407521.video_description: After having vowed for weeks to push into Gaza’s southern border town of Rafah, Israeli forces say they have taken control of the Palestinian side of Rafah crossing – a key strategic objective and the sole gateway between Egypt and Gaza for humanitarian aid. “At the moment we have operational control of the Gazan side of the Rafah crossing,” an Israeli military official said on Tuesday morning. “The operation is not over … I can’t give a timeline,” he added. The Israeli military also said late on Monday that it was conducting targeted strikes against Hamas in Rafah. The city’s Kuwaiti hospital said on Tuesday that 11 people had been killed and dozens of others injured in the strikes. Israel had earlier called for Palestinians in several neighbourhoods in eastern Rafah to evacuate before a ground excursion, triggering an exodus of thousands of people. The Israeli operation is taking place before a fresh round of indirect negotiations on a ceasefire in Cairo, and after Hamas announced its acceptance of an Egyptian-Qatari ceasefire proposal. Israeli officials said the terms did not meet its “core demands”, but that they would send a delegation for further talks. Follow the latest developments in our live blog via the link in bio.
